<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="387" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,342,727]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,365,414,439]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387">Redescription</emphasis>
(adapted and expanded from 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt" box="[735,910,414,439]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" refString="Schmidt, O. (1870) Grundzuge einer Spongien-Fauna des atlantischen Gebietes. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig, pp. iii - iv, 1 - 88, pls I - VI." type="book chapter" year="1870">
Schmidt, 
<number box="[850,910,415,439]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="1870.0">1870</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<number box="[928,960,414,439]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="53.0">53</number>
). The sponge is an irregular mass, not strikingly thick. Oxeas are very irregularly arranged only in young specimens. In the larger and older specimens these lie in tracts, having 
<number box="[450,478,487,511]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="40.0">40</number>
µm in diameter, and these carry abundant diancistras around, that are mostly erect (
<figureCitation box="[159,229,522,547]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1882,1904]" captionTargetBox="[223,1357,200,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[223,1357,200,1854]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Hamacantha (H.) schmidtii (Carter, 1882; Desmacella johnsoni (Bowerbank, 1864) sensu Schmidt, 1870), BMNH 1870.5. 3.28. A, Schmidt’s microscopic preparation analysed in the early 1990 ’ s. B, Larger diancistras forming a loose rosette. B, Larger diancistras erect on a tract of oxeas. C, Larger diancistra. D, Aberrant larger diancistra with a smaller diancistra lying on top of its lower extremity. E, intermediate diancistras. F – G, intermediate and smaller diancistras. Scales: C – D, 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/229218/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="387">
Fig. 
<number box="[213,229,523,547]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B). A rosette-like cluster of large diancistras was seen composed of eight spicules (
<figureCitation box="[1182,1251,522,547]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1882,1904]" captionTargetBox="[223,1357,200,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[223,1357,200,1854]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Hamacantha (H.) schmidtii (Carter, 1882; Desmacella johnsoni (Bowerbank, 1864) sensu Schmidt, 1870), BMNH 1870.5. 3.28. A, Schmidt’s microscopic preparation analysed in the early 1990 ’ s. B, Larger diancistras forming a loose rosette. B, Larger diancistras erect on a tract of oxeas. C, Larger diancistra. D, Aberrant larger diancistra with a smaller diancistra lying on top of its lower extremity. E, intermediate diancistras. F – G, intermediate and smaller diancistras. Scales: C – D, 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/229218/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="387">
Fig. 
<number box="[1236,1251,523,547]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
C). Oxeas, 
<number pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="403.15" valueMax="416.3" valueMin="390.0">
390– 
<emphasis box="[151,214,558,582]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="387">416.3</emphasis>
</number>
– 
<number box="[228,269,558,583]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="495.0">495</number>
µm long and 
<number box="[427,525,559,583]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="10.100000000000001" valueMax="10.8" valueMin="9.4">
9.4– 
<emphasis box="[476,525,559,583]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="387">10.8</emphasis>
</number>
– 
<number box="[540,588,559,583]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="12.8">12.8</number>
µm thick (
<figureCitation box="[712,780,558,583]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1882,1904]" captionTargetBox="[223,1357,200,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[223,1357,200,1854]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Hamacantha (H.) schmidtii (Carter, 1882; Desmacella johnsoni (Bowerbank, 1864) sensu Schmidt, 1870), BMNH 1870.5. 3.28. A, Schmidt’s microscopic preparation analysed in the early 1990 ’ s. B, Larger diancistras forming a loose rosette. B, Larger diancistras erect on a tract of oxeas. C, Larger diancistra. D, Aberrant larger diancistra with a smaller diancistra lying on top of its lower extremity. E, intermediate diancistras. F – G, intermediate and smaller diancistras. Scales: C – D, 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/229218/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="387">
Fig. 
<number box="[765,780,559,583]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
C). Larger diancistras (
<figureCitation box="[1038,1105,558,583]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1882,1904]" captionTargetBox="[223,1357,200,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[223,1357,200,1854]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Hamacantha (H.) schmidtii (Carter, 1882; Desmacella johnsoni (Bowerbank, 1864) sensu Schmidt, 1870), BMNH 1870.5. 3.28. A, Schmidt’s microscopic preparation analysed in the early 1990 ’ s. B, Larger diancistras forming a loose rosette. B, Larger diancistras erect on a tract of oxeas. C, Larger diancistra. D, Aberrant larger diancistra with a smaller diancistra lying on top of its lower extremity. E, intermediate diancistras. F – G, intermediate and smaller diancistras. Scales: C – D, 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/229218/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="387">
Fig. 
<number box="[1091,1105,559,583]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B–E), stouter, nearly straight, fimbriae and notches well marked, hooks each about 
<number box="[750,760,595,619]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[771,785,595,619]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="3.0">3</number>
total length, 
<number box="[935,1052,595,619]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="113.55" valueMax="118.1" valueMin="109.0">
109– 
<emphasis box="[991,1052,595,619]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="387">118.1</emphasis>
</number>
– 
<number box="[1067,1108,595,619]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="124.0">124</number>
µm. Intermediate diancistras (
<figureCitation box="[159,229,630,655]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1882,1904]" captionTargetBox="[223,1357,200,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[223,1357,200,1854]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Hamacantha (H.) schmidtii (Carter, 1882; Desmacella johnsoni (Bowerbank, 1864) sensu Schmidt, 1870), BMNH 1870.5. 3.28. A, Schmidt’s microscopic preparation analysed in the early 1990 ’ s. B, Larger diancistras forming a loose rosette. B, Larger diancistras erect on a tract of oxeas. C, Larger diancistra. D, Aberrant larger diancistra with a smaller diancistra lying on top of its lower extremity. E, intermediate diancistras. F – G, intermediate and smaller diancistras. Scales: C – D, 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/229218/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="387">
Fig. 
<number box="[215,229,631,655]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
E–H), slender, contorted and markedly bent in the middle, hooks over 
<number box="[1063,1091,631,655]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="40.0">40</number>
% total spicule length, sharp extremities, fimbriae clearly seen on shaft but not apparent on hooks, 
<number box="[928,956,666,691]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="44.0">44</number>
–50.0– 
<number box="[1033,1060,666,691]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="54.0">54</number>
Μm. Smaller diancistras (
<figureCitation box="[1346,1413,666,691]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1882,1904]" captionTargetBox="[223,1357,200,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[223,1357,200,1854]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Hamacantha (H.) schmidtii (Carter, 1882; Desmacella johnsoni (Bowerbank, 1864) sensu Schmidt, 1870), BMNH 1870.5. 3.28. A, Schmidt’s microscopic preparation analysed in the early 1990 ’ s. B, Larger diancistras forming a loose rosette. B, Larger diancistras erect on a tract of oxeas. C, Larger diancistra. D, Aberrant larger diancistra with a smaller diancistra lying on top of its lower extremity. E, intermediate diancistras. F – G, intermediate and smaller diancistras. Scales: C – D, 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/229218/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="387">
Fig. 
<number box="[1398,1413,667,691]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
E, G–H), same general shape as intermediate category, but fimbriae not obvious in any part, 
<number box="[1156,1247,702,727]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="31.25" valueMax="36.5" valueMin="26.0">
26– 
<emphasis box="[1198,1247,702,726]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="387">36.5</emphasis>
</number>
– 
<number box="[1262,1289,703,727]" pageId="3" pageNumber="387" value="41.0">41</number>
µm.
</paragraph>
